[36m(main_task pid=143845)[0m Krakow, the ancient city located in the north-central region of Poland, has undergone several phases in its role as the capital of the country. The city's prominence as a capital can be traced back to the 10th century, when it began to emerge as a significant power in Eastern Europe. 
[36m(main_task pid=143845)[0m 
[36m(main_task pid=143845)[0m In the 13th century, Krakow rose to prominence as the capital of the Polish Kingdom. The first Polish king, Mieszko I, was crowned in 1025 in the city of Gniezno, which was later transferred to Krakow in 1040. This marked the beginning of Krakow's historic and crucial role as the central political and administrative hub of Poland.
[36m(main_task pid=143845)[0m 
[36m(main_task pid=143845)[0m Under the reign of King Casimir III the Great, who ruled from 1333 to 1370, Krakow became even more influential and an essential center of culture, arts, and learning in the region. His reign saw the flourishing of the Teutonic Order, which had a significant impact on the city's expansion and development.
[36m(main_task pid=143845)[0m 
[36m(main_task pid=143845)[0m Throughout the Middle Ages and the Renaissance, Krakow continued to be the capital of Poland. However, during the reign of King Jan III Sobieski in the 18th century, the capital shifted to Warsaw, leaving Krakow behind.
[36m(main_task pid=143845)[0m 
[36m(main_task pid=143845)[0m However, in 1918, Poland gained independence once again, and Krakow emerged as the capital of the newly established Polish state, a role that it retained throughout World War II until the communist regime changed the capital to Warsaw in 1945.
[36m(main_task pid=143845)[0m 
[36m(main_task pid=143845)[0m It wasn't until the late 20th century that Krakow gradually regained its significance as a cultural and economic center in Poland, and even today, it remains a vital part of Poland's history and identity as a city.
[36m(main_task pid=143845)[0m 
[36m(main_task pid=143845)[0m So, to answer your question, Krakow was a capital of Poland at different time periods, but the first notable capital for most of its existence was during the reigns of King Casimir III the Great and King Jan III Sobieski, and the city again became Poland's capital in 1918 until 1945.
