[36m(main_task pid=143845)[0m The Maple Leaf Gardens was a Canadian sporting venue designed by architect Walter Pomeroy Bailey and constructed in Toronto in 1931-1932. It was officially dedicated by the Toronto Maple Leafs to serve as their main arena for ice hockey, as well as for exhibitions. The arena was also used for indoor swimming, basketball, boxing, figure skating, and judo matches. When the sports club moved to a larger venue in 1999, the Olympic Auditorium in Yorkville was converted into an exhibition space. After the arena was refurbished, it was renamed the Air Canada Centre (ACC). The centre continues to be used for the professional ice hockey team, the Toronto Maple Leafs. It is also the home of the Toronto Raptors NBA basketball team. On January 5, 2008, The ACC has become the first European-based arena to install high-definition video boards.
