[36m(main_task pid=143845)[0m Doc 3(Title: "Place Masséna") Place Masséna The Place Masséna is a historic square in Nice, Alpes-Maritimes, France. It was named for André Masséna. Its layout was designed by Joseph Vernier in 1843-1844. The Place Masséna is the main square of the city. Before the Paillon River was covered over, the Pont-Neuf ("New Bridge") on Place Masséna was the longest bridge in Europe. North of the square is the Opera House and Grand Promenade. Its official name is Place Nationale, used to evoke the old name of the town, Nice-Ville. South of the Place Masséna is the Promenade des Anglais, the second-longest promenade in France (after the Promenade des Arrondissements in Toulon). Between Place Masséna and the Promenade des Anglais is the municipal golf course. Today, it is often called "the town's square". The administrative buildings of the Port of Nice, including the Tour de Port, are located to the left of the square. (http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Place_Mass%C3%A9na)
