[36m(main_task pid=143845)[0m Doc 2(Title: "Ulrich Schiefer") Ulrich Schiefer Ulrich Schiefer (* September 10, 1952, in Lauffen am Neckar) is a German rural and development sociologist and anthropologist. His main interests are development policy and international development cooperation, especially their impact on sub-Saharan Africa. Ulrich Schiefer studied sociology with Christian Sigrist and Song Du-yul at the Westfälische Wilhelms-Universität in Münster, Social anthropology with Rüdiger Schott and Ulrich Köhler, Sinology with Ulrich Unger as well as Communication studies. After his Magister degree in sociology (1977) on Agricultural cooperatives in the People's Republic of China, he worked as a United Nations volunteer in urban and regional planning in Guinea-Bissau.
[36m(main_task pid=143845)[0m Doc 3(Title: "Reinhart Heinrich") Reinhart Heinrich Reinhart Heinrich (24 April 1946 – 23 October 2006) was a German biophysicist. He was professor at the Humboldt University of Berlin, and best known as a founder of metabolic control theory. Among his services to the scientific community, Reinhart was associate editor of ""PLoS Computational Biology"". His far-reaching theoretical work on metabolism, signal transduction, and other cellular processes has made him one of the most influential forerunners of systems biology.
[36m(main_task pid=143845)[0m Doc 4(Title: "François de La Borie") François de La Borie François de La Borie (born March 22, 1960) is a French astronaut and fighter pilot. He is most often credited with the role of spotting and coordinating the UFOs observed during the OV-105/KA46 mission of STS-104. François de La Borie was born in 1960 in Compiègne, France. He was designated as a fighter pilot and received his first plane at the age of twenty. He trained at the École de pilotage de Médecines, a flight academy. In 1987, he was called up for military service. François de La Borie joined the French Air Force. In the Air Force, he first worked as a co-pilot before being appointed in-flight radio operator. He received a title of squadron commander, where he first saw the SASO mission as a payload specialist. In 1995, he joined the French space agency CNES and was assigned in 2002 as pilot and commander of the Soyuz TMA-5. In 2006, he was appointed to head the mission of STS-117/3.
